02:14:17.350 --> 02:14:18.580
Tim Sackton: you know.

1791
02:14:18.680 --> 02:14:25.289
Tim Sackton: what I have promised you. You've seen what I've shown you. You know what's waiting for us.

1792
02:14:25.540 --> 02:14:28.369
Tim Sackton: We will march, night and day.

1793
02:14:28.650 --> 02:14:32.540
Tim Sackton: My magic. Our magic. Limbo will keep us safe.

1794
02:14:33.210 --> 02:14:36.909
Tim Sackton: In this march. I promise you that.

1795
02:14:37.580 --> 02:14:40.529
Tim Sackton: And when we arrive, you will have vengeance.

1796
02:14:41.470 --> 02:14:42.709
Tim Sackton: You will see.

1797
02:14:43.380 --> 02:14:44.290
Tim Sackton: These.

1798
02:14:45.270 --> 02:14:49.759
Tim Sackton: Foolish creatures who think they can call upon the power of the gods?

1799
02:14:50.920 --> 02:14:53.130
Tim Sackton: The gods do not scare us.

1800
02:14:54.500 --> 02:14:59.710
Tim Sackton: Chaos existed before any god came out of its primordial power.

1801
02:14:59.890 --> 02:15:06.369
Tim Sackton: Chaos is stronger than any magic they can bring to bear. Do not fear these things.

1802
02:15:06.640 --> 02:15:07.870
Tim Sackton: Vengeance.

1803
02:15:08.090 --> 02:15:09.679
Tim Sackton: will be yours.

1804
02:15:10.080 --> 02:15:11.620
Tim Sackton: Promise you that.

1805
02:15:15.650 --> 02:15:23.540
Tim Sackton: There's, like… You know, about half the army is, like, sort of… Totally sold by this.

1806
02:15:24.560 --> 02:15:27.019
Tim Sackton: About half the army is kinda…

1807
02:15:28.360 --> 02:15:38.209
Tim Sackton: sure, lady. But nobody's willing to, like… the only people… nobody's, like, actively disagreeing, right? It's just, you can see from the…

1808
02:15:39.220 --> 02:15:45.229
Tim Sackton: you know, the… the scrying, like, it's just… it's not full-throated cheers across the entire arm.

1809
02:15:45.230 --> 02:15:47.160
David S. Kong: Our tactics are working. This is awesome.

1810
02:15:49.870 --> 02:15:51.610
David S. Kong: We're sowing seeds of dissension.

1811
02:15:52.090 --> 02:15:53.130
Mike: Absolutely.

1812
02:15:53.770 --> 02:15:56.619
David S. Kong: Hell yeah.

1813
02:15:57.280 --> 02:15:57.810
Mike: Alright.

1814
02:15:58.150 --> 02:16:04.050
Tim Sackton: The structure seems to be reassembling, and it's only, like, 1.30 in the afternoon, so this is clearly not…

1815
02:16:04.510 --> 02:16:05.450
Tim Sackton: Standard.

1816
02:16:06.150 --> 02:16:06.640
Mike: Yeah, yeah.

1817
02:16:06.900 --> 02:16:07.760
Tim Sackton: a behavior.

1818
02:16:07.760 --> 02:16:10.310
Mike: She might mean it about go day and night.

1819
02:16:11.470 --> 02:16:12.790
Audio shared by Tim Sackton: In the sense that…

1820
02:16:12.790 --> 02:16:15.980
Mike: Clearly the way to be the safest that they could be.

1821
02:16:16.110 --> 02:16:21.179
Mike: Is to just stay inside the structure and barely ever stop.

1822
02:16:21.290 --> 02:16:23.400
Mike: It must be rough for her troops, but…

1823
02:16:25.020 --> 02:16:26.200
David S. Kong: Can't be good for morale.

1824
02:16:26.370 --> 02:16:27.120
Mike: Nope.

1825
02:16:31.210 --> 02:16:31.670
Tim Sackton: So…

1826
02:16:34.100 --> 02:16:37.749
Mike: We have to show up tomorrow to, like…

1827
02:16:38.070 --> 02:16:39.290
David S. Kong: Oh, yeah. See if…

1828
02:16:39.320 --> 02:16:41.919
Mike: She shows up for single combat or not, right?

1829
02:16:42.250 --> 02:16:43.129
David S. Kong: Of course.

1830
02:16:43.400 --> 02:16:49.480
Mike: Do we bring some people with us? Like, do we bring a group of animal-shaped people in case there's, like…

1831
02:16:50.370 --> 02:16:51.940
Mike: Do we want witnesses?

1832
02:16:54.320 --> 02:16:55.530
David S. Kong: What do you mean, witnesses?

1833
02:16:55.700 --> 02:16:58.700
Mike: Sorry, not really witnesses, but more like…

1834
02:16:58.820 --> 02:17:02.859
Mike: You know, 50 volunteers shaped as eagles to go

1835
02:17:03.730 --> 02:17:08.930
Mike: you know, fight off the Hawk guards that are shaped as rhinoceroses to, like.

1836
02:17:09.250 --> 02:17:18.309
Mike: form a circle around us so that in combat, the hobgoblins can't rush us, and something like that, right? Or is it… I mean, I bet you we could get volunteers.

1837
02:17:19.049 --> 02:17:25.529
David S. Kong: Well, I doubt… I doubt the Hobgoblins are gonna be super happy allowing us to, like, encircle their leader, like, in a…

1838
02:17:27.070 --> 02:17:33.029
David S. Kong: part of, like, 50 elephants surrounding them. Trust us, it'll be fine.

1839
02:17:33.860 --> 02:17:37.080
Mike: I mean, our goal is to kill her, so it's not really gonna be fine, right?

1840
02:17:37.600 --> 02:17:42.890
David S. Kong: Oh, yeah, so… but let's… but we, I mean, you know, we should honor the fair combat, so…

1841
02:17:43.049 --> 02:17:44.519
Mike: No, yeah, that's true.

1842
02:17:44.520 --> 02:17:50.319
David S. Kong: But I agree, if she doesn't come to fight us, though, we need to unleash something on her, on the army. So…

1843
02:17:50.320 --> 02:17:53.700
Mike: I mean, I'm trying to think of what else we could do to get inside the…

1844
02:17:55.290 --> 02:18:01.080
Mike: There's not a lot. If they're just traveling inside the structure, there's not… a lot.

1845
02:18:01.440 --> 02:18:02.989
Mike: That we have, that would…

1846
02:18:02.990 --> 02:18:09.979
David S. Kong: It didn't… I mean, we said though, right, like, because essentially, it's made out of chaos metal, right, the centipede is, right? Same stuff that she's made out of.

1847
02:18:10.299 --> 02:18:10.759
Mike: Yeah.

1848
02:18:10.760 --> 02:18:12.450
David S. Kong: So, lightning would work.

1849
02:18:13.719 --> 02:18:19.759
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Or what about, like, Radiant damage? I feel like radiant… stuff. Tends to… get through…

1850
02:18:19.760 --> 02:18:26.200
Tim Sackton: She is resistant to radiant damage. She is resistant to radiant and cold, immune to fire, necrotic, and poison.

1851
02:18:26.370 --> 02:18:29.340
David S. Kong: So what is she… what is she not… Resistant or mean to.

1852
02:18:29.440 --> 02:18:33.770
Tim Sackton: So, like, thunder… Lightning… acid.

1853
02:18:37.469 --> 02:18:40.999
David S. Kong: or lightning acid, what else do we have to work… is that… are those the main things that we have to work with?

1854
02:18:41.000 --> 02:18:45.539
Tim Sackton: I mean, just normal, like, bludgeoning, slashing, piercing, like, that sort of stuff.

1855
02:18:46.160 --> 02:18:48.029
David S. Kong: So, we must have other stuff.

1856
02:18:52.290 --> 02:18:52.799
David S. Kong: What?

1857
02:18:52.809 --> 02:18:55.579
Tim Sackton: Yeah, what a… psychic? Psychic damage?

1858
02:18:55.799 --> 02:18:56.499
David S. Kong: What is it?

1859
02:18:58.799 --> 02:18:59.559
Audio shared by Tim Sackton: Here.

1860
02:18:59.559 --> 02:19:08.069
Mike: I mean, the problem is that it's hard to impact them, because they're all… Tucked inside this… place, right?

1861
02:19:08.480 --> 02:19:09.049
Eric R: Hmm.

1862
02:19:10.160 --> 02:19:16.959
Mike: So if they're just traveling, and they never stop, than…

1863
02:19:19.120 --> 02:19:21.850
Mike: It's not obvious to me what we do to hurt them.

1864
02:19:23.090 --> 02:19:29.179
Eric R: We slingshot Seeker 4 over top of it, and while in the air, he casts the heat metal.

1865
02:19:30.959 --> 02:19:33.699
David S. Kong: Heat metal's not gonna… I mean, we could try heat metal, right?

1866
02:19:34.150 --> 02:19:36.090
David S. Kong: They're… it's resistant. They're resistant to me.

1867
02:19:36.090 --> 02:19:38.450
Mike: But it's probably… we're pretty sure it's not gonna work.

1868
02:19:39.180 --> 02:19:41.209
Tim Sackton: He's immune to fire damage.

1869
02:19:41.219 --> 02:19:42.179
Mike: So we assumed…

1870
02:19:42.180 --> 02:19:48.010
Tim Sackton: correlates with chaos metal properties. It's very unlikely fire is gonna heat.

1871
02:19:48.160 --> 02:19:53.200
David S. Kong: We just said, we just said thunder, Lightning, Acid, Psychic, Regular, Bludgeon Piercing.

1872
02:19:54.050 --> 02:19:54.959
David S. Kong: That's what we got to work with.

1873
02:19:55.600 --> 02:19:58.510
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): What about… what about attacking the…

1874
02:19:59.060 --> 02:20:07.489
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): the construct thing itself. Like, if we had a herd of a hundred giant walruses, like, smashing into, like, bludgeoning the side of it.

1875
02:20:07.490 --> 02:20:09.660
David S. Kong: Yeah, exactly, exactly. I'm with that.

1876
02:20:09.660 --> 02:20:10.750
Eric R: Hmm…

1877
02:20:11.950 --> 02:20:13.890
Mike: I mean, it's not a crazy idea.

1878
02:20:15.080 --> 02:20:17.109
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): So what about something just like…

1879
02:20:17.440 --> 02:20:23.700
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Trying to damage that thing itself, like a bunch of catapults, or dropping rocks. When does Vinder Sharna get here?

1880
02:20:24.000 --> 02:20:25.000
Tim Sackton: 2 days.

1881
02:20:26.780 --> 02:20:28.490
Eric R: We're definitely gonna drop rocks.

1882
02:20:38.680 --> 02:20:47.470
Eric R: So, what's the story with Lightning? Could I do… Anything with my… Wish ability.

1883
02:20:50.550 --> 02:20:51.950
Mike: Any waging effects?

1884
02:20:52.630 --> 02:20:54.229
Eric R: That's the nastiest lightning spell.

1885
02:20:59.820 --> 02:21:00.760
Mike: Good question.

1886
02:21:05.230 --> 02:21:06.100
Eric R: Let's see…

1887
02:21:06.110 --> 02:21:10.800
Tim Sackton: I mean… Don't forget, you can… Change.

1888
02:21:11.090 --> 02:21:12.819
Tim Sackton: Spells with your glove.

1889
02:21:14.500 --> 02:21:15.330
Mike: And…

1890
02:21:15.330 --> 02:21:17.459
Eric R: Alright, I didn't think of that.

1891
02:21:18.210 --> 02:21:19.110
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Paul Lightning…

1892
02:21:19.110 --> 02:21:19.790
Eric R: still.

1893
02:21:20.160 --> 02:21:24.339
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): gives… 100 rounds of 3D10 lightning bolts?

1894
02:21:26.480 --> 02:21:28.670
Tim Sackton: 10… 10 rounds.

1895
02:21:29.030 --> 02:21:30.269
Tim Sackton: It's 10 minutes. Right.

1896
02:21:30.470 --> 02:21:31.360
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): 10 minutes.

1897
02:21:31.360 --> 02:21:34.189
Tim Sackton: Okay. But it's a fixed area, you can't move it.

1898
02:21:35.210 --> 02:21:37.179
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Oh, that's true. 60 foot radius.

1899
02:21:42.010 --> 02:21:45.400
Eric R: Wait, so I can… No, miss.

1900
02:21:45.970 --> 02:21:51.479
Tim Sackton: You can… Convert any spell to acid, cold, fire, lightning, or thunder.

1901
02:21:59.120 --> 02:22:04.670
Eric R: So can I make… Could be like an acid tsunami.

1902
02:22:13.640 --> 02:22:16.860
Eric R: So just, what's the biggest area of effect?

1903
02:22:17.040 --> 02:22:20.330
Eric R: Of a damage spell that we could get inside the thing.

1904
02:22:20.330 --> 02:22:23.749
Mike: It's just, I don't know how we get any spells inside the thing, right?

1905
02:22:25.580 --> 02:22:28.669
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Do we know that it protects from magic, or are we just…

1906
02:22:28.790 --> 02:22:37.660
Tim Sackton: Yes. Well, it's total cover, right? So you can't target… you can't place a spell inside the compartment.

1907
02:22:39.390 --> 02:22:49.300
Tim Sackton: Because it's… it's within total cover. Now, whether something can damage the creature is a different question. You presume that fire and…

1908
02:22:49.450 --> 02:22:58.529
Tim Sackton: Cold and radiant and necrotic, and poison can't damage the creature, but… Would acid damage… actually damage the…

1909
02:22:58.760 --> 02:23:02.080
Tim Sackton: centipede, like, the Mecha Centipede itself?

1910
02:23:02.420 --> 02:23:06.630
Tim Sackton: Like, that's an open question. You don't have an answer one way or another.

1911
02:23:08.720 --> 02:23:12.580
Tim Sackton: But you can't… there's no way you can target a spell inside the…

1912
02:23:14.540 --> 02:23:21.000
Tim Sackton: inside this thing itself, because it has… it's total cover. You can't target anything that has total cover for it.

1913
02:23:27.910 --> 02:23:34.420
Eric R: So if we put a wall of fire that we flavor as wall of acid, Cutting through.

1914
02:23:35.960 --> 02:23:37.260
Eric R: obstruction.

1915
02:23:40.470 --> 02:23:42.429
Eric R: Does it penetrate it?

1916
02:23:44.980 --> 02:23:46.529
Tim Sackton: No, I mean…

1917
02:23:50.940 --> 02:23:54.470
Tim Sackton: I mean, you could… you can't… I don't think you can put,

1918
02:23:55.310 --> 02:23:57.899
Tim Sackton: Well, yeah, you could, but it would not…

1919
02:23:59.130 --> 02:24:02.219
Tim Sackton: The spell wouldn't appear inside the…

1920
02:24:03.560 --> 02:24:04.170
Eric R: Right.

1921
02:24:09.760 --> 02:24:15.039
Tim Sackton: Right, it's like, you know, you can't make part of a wall of fire appear inside somebody's intestines.

1922
02:24:17.570 --> 02:24:19.299
Eric R: That's oddly specific, Tim.

1923
02:24:19.510 --> 02:24:21.520
Tim Sackton: Well, it's exactly the same, right? It's…

1924
02:24:21.670 --> 02:24:25.189
Tim Sackton: If something… if you swallow something, it has total cover to everything.

1925
02:24:25.540 --> 02:24:26.190
Eric R: Right.

1926
02:24:27.690 --> 02:24:33.369
Tim Sackton: A person's intestines wouldn't be very relevant, but, like, you know, an ice worm's intestines, which…

1927
02:24:33.580 --> 02:24:35.169
Tim Sackton: At least one of you.

1928
02:24:35.990 --> 02:24:38.410
Tim Sackton: Was it, you know, spent time in.

1929
02:24:39.030 --> 02:24:39.940
Eric R: Brisbane, actually?

1930
02:24:39.940 --> 02:24:41.429
Tim Sackton: I think it was Riswin, actually.

1931
02:24:50.860 --> 02:24:54.890
Tim Sackton: So, it's, like, mid-afternoon right now.

1932
02:24:54.890 --> 02:25:00.760
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Wait a minute, wait a minute, though. If the tsunami is 300 feet tall, like…

1933
02:25:01.800 --> 02:25:09.279
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): I don't know, like, I guess I, like, I'm getting caught up on the… and tell me if I should just drop it, like, I'm getting caught up on the total cover thing, like…

1934
02:25:09.830 --> 02:25:13.039
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): 300 feet long, 300 feet high, 50 feet thick.

1935
02:25:13.630 --> 02:25:19.270
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): like… Just because we can't see… Like, one particular…

1936
02:25:20.000 --> 02:25:21.750
Mike: No, but they're… we already.

1937
02:25:22.080 --> 02:25:23.099
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Eat the rest of it.

1938
02:25:23.100 --> 02:25:32.340
Tim Sackton: They already protected themselves from a tsunami by climbing inside It… it's like… Y-you know.

1939
02:25:33.270 --> 02:25:34.980
Tim Sackton: If you were in a…

1940
02:25:35.030 --> 02:25:36.350
Mike: They're in a tank.

1941
02:25:36.670 --> 02:25:39.969
Tim Sackton: You're in a tank, and a tsunami washes past the tank.

1942
02:25:41.220 --> 02:25:43.910
Tim Sackton: The tsunami washes past the tank.

1943
02:25:43.910 --> 02:25:48.210
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): No, no, I understand, but I'm thinking of, like, when they were in camp, like in the attack yesterday.

1944
02:25:48.470 --> 02:25:53.059
Tim Sackton: Oh, yes. Theoretically, maybe you could have tried Tsunami instead of Earthquake yesterday.

1945
02:25:53.060 --> 02:25:53.690
Mike: Yes, yes.

1946
02:25:53.690 --> 02:25:54.380
Rev David Schwartz (he/him): Start iron.

1947
02:25:54.380 --> 02:25:55.060
Eric R: Cool.

1948
02:25:55.510 --> 02:25:59.100
Mike: We were just trying to not repeat our tricks. Maybe that was a mistake.

1949
02:25:59.430 --> 02:26:00.190
Mike: Right.

1950
02:26:01.120 --> 02:26:01.870
Mike: But…

1951
02:26:02.220 --> 02:26:09.919
Mike: But I think, I mean, the challenge is, if we think that her speech was basically to say, we are traveling without stopping now.

1952
02:26:10.090 --> 02:26:11.050
Eric R: Right?

1953
02:26:12.410 --> 02:26:20.530
Mike: then it becomes a little bit tricky to understand. Like, it's gonna be, I think, quite difficult.

1954
02:26:20.710 --> 02:26:23.170
Mike: To impact them with spells.

1955
02:26:23.750 --> 02:26:33.399
Mike: inside the creature, because there are basically no spells that you can… In general, in D&D, it's not possible to cast a spell into a space that you can't…

1956
02:26:33.870 --> 02:26:34.670
Mike: get to.

1957
02:26:35.430 --> 02:26:35.970
Eric R: Right.

1958
02:26:36.410 --> 02:26:42.089
Mike: Like, you can't… just even inside a closed room, if you're in a closed room, you can't cast spells on the other side of the…

1959
02:26:42.640 --> 02:26:45.979
Tim Sackton: Right, there are some… I mean, clairvoyance is an exception, for example, but…

1960
02:26:45.980 --> 02:26:46.520
Mike: separate.

1961
02:26:46.520 --> 02:26:48.050
Tim Sackton: Generally speaking, that's true.

1962
02:26:55.790 --> 02:27:01.070
Mike: So, it becomes difficult. I mean, I think… I think we rest, right?

1963
02:27:09.220 --> 02:27:10.040
Mike: Right?

1964
02:27:10.240 --> 02:27:13.519
Mike: I mean, I don't know what else we do other than…

1965
02:27:14.370 --> 02:27:17.840
Mike: Go back tomorrow and see if she comes out to challenge us.

1966
02:27:18.220 --> 02:27:27.150
Mike: Right? And if she doesn't… It's just a little bit unclear to me what we…

1967
02:27:28.630 --> 02:27:34.090
Mike: What we can do to… I mean…

1968
02:27:35.110 --> 02:27:36.320
Eric R: Nice.

1969
02:27:37.540 --> 02:27:40.320
Eric R: I wonder if we can shear off some of the spikes.

1970
02:27:43.960 --> 02:27:45.019
Eric R: You know what I mean?

1971
02:27:45.040 --> 02:27:46.210
Audio shared by Tim Sackton: So they couldn't…

1972
02:27:46.210 --> 02:27:47.470
Eric R: Make their rift.

1973
02:27:49.180 --> 02:27:50.040
Eric R: While at rest.

1974
02:27:53.680 --> 02:27:57.690
Mike: I mean, if we can catch them resting, right, we can do all kinds of stuff.

1975
02:28:00.030 --> 02:28:03.510
Mike: I feel like if we don't catch them… resting?

1976
02:28:04.080 --> 02:28:04.770
Mike: It's not…

1977
02:28:14.160 --> 02:28:16.700
Mike: We could try… we could try reversing gravity.

1978
02:28:17.710 --> 02:28:20.060
Eric R: What about the time when they're setting up their camp?

1979
02:28:22.670 --> 02:28:24.760
Eric R: Like, they'll have to get out.

1980
02:28:26.130 --> 02:28:27.820
Eric R: And be vulnerable, briefly.

1981
02:28:28.400 --> 02:28:31.500
Mike: Right, I just… don't know if they're going to set up a camp.

1982
02:28:31.700 --> 02:28:32.949
Eric R: Oh, right, right, right, they may not.

1983
02:28:34.250 --> 02:28:37.609
Mike: That's kind of the problem. They might decide to not set up a camp at all.

1984
02:28:44.110 --> 02:28:52.209
Mike: I mean, something like Reverse Gravity, if you go into the spell's area of effect, you're not immune to it, even though you're inside.

1985
02:28:52.210 --> 02:28:52.720
Tim Sackton: Right.

1986
02:28:52.960 --> 02:28:53.650
Mike: Right?

1987
02:28:54.840 --> 02:28:56.720
Mike: I just don't know how much good it would do.

1988
02:29:04.160 --> 02:29:06.719
Tim Sackton: Well, make a decision about what you want to do.

1989
02:29:13.660 --> 02:29:18.379
Eric R: Delete, so we don't have any effective attacks while they're inside the thing.

1990
02:29:19.640 --> 02:29:20.400
Eric R: I could…

1991
02:29:23.650 --> 02:29:25.620
Eric R: We're gonna go, anyway.

1992
02:29:26.740 --> 02:29:30.960
Eric R: I could clairvoyance inside the thing to see what it looks like in there, at least.

1993
02:29:32.250 --> 02:29:32.920
Mike: Yeah?

1994
02:29:33.910 --> 02:29:34.960
David S. Kong: That's a great idea.

1995
02:29:37.570 --> 02:29:38.360
Mike: Yeah?

1996
02:29:38.360 --> 02:29:43.580
David S. Kong: I mean, this would be kinda crazy. We could also just teleport inside there and just start fighting all the troops.

1997
02:29:44.490 --> 02:29:45.420
